The Birds Who Sought the King — ʿAṭṭār and the Imaginal Journey to Qaf

Commentary

ʿAṭṭār begins with a parliament of birds. The image is simple enough for a child and vast enough for metaphysics: every bird of the world gathers because something is missing. They have wings, songs, colours, habits, excuses, and instincts, but no king. Their world is full of movement and yet lacks a centre.

This is the first imaginal gesture of The Conference of the Birds: the soul is not one thing. It is a flock. Every faculty has a voice. Every attachment becomes a bird. Every bird has a reason not to travel. The journey to the Sīmurgh is therefore not merely a quest for God, but the re-ordering of the whole inner parliament.

