The Parliament of Birds

Commentary

The many faculties of the soul gathered into one council.

Commentary

The birds are not decorative animals. They are psychic forms. Each bird speaks from a particular limitation: pride, fear, love of comfort, fascination with beauty, attachment to status, piety that hides cowardice. The whole human being is placed on stage as a flock.

This is why ʿAṭṭār’s poem works so perfectly as an imaginal source text. The self does not appear as an abstract ego. It appears as a field of figures. The soul can hear itself because its own forces have become visible and speakable.

The Hoopoe’s role is therefore not to provide information. The Hoopoe is the inner guide who sees the disorder of the parliament and points toward the hidden king.

