Commentary

The world mountain Qaf places the journey inside the same symbolic geography as Corbin’s eighth climate. Qaf is not merely a mountain. It is the edge of ordinary orientation. To go there is to leave the flat world of habitual perception and enter a geography where the soul’s states become landscapes.

The birds want a king, but the king is not found by argument. He is found by transformation. The poem’s method is therefore imaginal pedagogy: each bird exposes its excuse, the Hoopoe answers with a story, and the story turns the excuse into a mirror.

The soul learns by seeing itself from the outside.

