The Mountain of Qaf

Commentary

The summit of the world where the seeker discovers that the king was hidden in the seekers themselves.

Commentary

The final secret of the poem is contained in its number. The birds seek the Sīmurgh, but only thirty birds arrive. In Persian, sī murgh can mean “thirty birds.” The king they sought appears through the purified remnant of the seekers themselves.

This is not a cheap pun. It is the imaginal logic of the whole work. The symbol is not an external object to be possessed. It is a transformation in the structure of seeing. The birds do not find a king as one more thing in the world. They become capable of beholding the king because the false birds have fallen away.

The path to Qaf is therefore a method of reduction. Excuses are burned off. False identities fall. The many are gathered until the hidden unity can look back through them.

