Commentary

The great danger in reading The Conference of the Birds is to reduce it to allegory. Allegory would say: this bird means this vice, this valley means this stage, the Sīmurgh means God. That is not wrong, but it is too flat.

The poem is more than a code. It is a machine for imaginative self-recognition. It makes the reader feel the excuses from within, then places those excuses in a visible bird-form. The poem does not merely tell the seeker to transcend the self. It stages the self as a parliament and then sends the whole parliament through fire, absence, longing, terror, and loss.

The imaginal realm here is the theatre in which the soul can finally see itself truthfully.

