The Third Thing Born in the Fire — Jung and the Transcendent Function

Commentary

Jung begins from division. The conscious personality has one attitude; the unconscious produces another. One side says yes, the other no. One side wants safety, the other image. One side wants control, the other symbol. The modern person suffers because the psyche has become a civil war.

The transcendent function is Jung’s name for the bridge that forms when the opposites are held together long enough for a third thing to be born. This is the psychological cousin of the imaginal realm: a middle space where image mediates between conscious intention and unconscious depth.

