The Red Book Chamber

Commentary

The inner chamber where unconscious figures become visible enough to answer.

Commentary

Jung’s active imagination is not a decorative technique. It begins in necessity. A conflict has become too alive to be solved by conscious reasoning alone. The unconscious brings images because the ego has reached the limit of its existing map.

This is why Jung’s method belongs in the Imaginarium. It treats images as events. A figure, fantasy, dream, painting, body movement, or inner voice is not dismissed as “just imagination.” It is approached as a carrier of psychic reality. But it is not obeyed blindly either.

The ego must enter relation. The image speaks. The ego answers. The tension between them becomes the furnace.

