Commentary

This passage saves active imagination from becoming merely visualisation. Jung’s method is not limited to sitting still and seeing pictures. It can become painting, speech, drama, dance, writing, sculpting, or ritual gesture.

The imaginal wants embodiment. An image that remains vague may fascinate the ego without transforming it. But when it is drawn, spoken, moved, or enacted, it becomes an object of relation. The ego can stand before it. The body can answer it. The symbol can begin to work.

This is why Jung is so useful for creative practice. The goal is not simply to interpret the image, but to give it a form in which it can transform the person who received it.

