The Eye That Must Become Sunlike — Plotinus and the Vision of Beauty

Commentary

Plotinus begins from beauty, but not beauty as decoration. Beauty is the trace by which the soul remembers its own origin. A beautiful body, action, sound, proportion, or thought is not simply pleasing. It awakens a hidden kinship between the soul and the intelligible world.

This is the Platonic foundation of imaginal perception. The visible is not rejected. It becomes a ladder. Beauty draws the soul inward and upward until perception itself is purified.

