Commentary

The soul as a hidden work of art uncovered by purification.

Commentary

Plotinus does not tell the reader to imagine beauty externally. He tells the reader to become capable of seeing it. The eye must be changed before the vision can occur.

This is crucial for the Imaginarium. The imaginal is not accessed by adding fantasy to perception. It is accessed by refining the perceiver. The object may be luminous, but the eye must be made adequate to it.

The soul becomes “self-gathered.” That phrase is the practice. Scattered attention cannot perceive the higher image. The soul must call itself back from dispersion until it becomes one enough to see.

