The Sunlike Eye

Commentary

The organ of perception transformed into likeness with what it beholds.

Commentary

This is the law of imaginal perception in its classical form: like knows like. The eye cannot see the sun unless it becomes sunlike. The soul cannot see Beauty unless it becomes beautiful.

That means the organ of perception is ethical, aesthetic, and spiritual at once. To perceive higher realities, one does not merely need information. One needs purification, likeness, affinity.

This is why traditions of imaginal work always include discipline. Without discipline, imagination becomes projection. With discipline, imagination becomes a faculty of participation.

