Commentary

Plotinus gives the vertical axis of the imaginal. Beauty in the world is not discarded. It is followed. The beautiful form becomes a sign of the higher Beauty from which it descends.

This is not abstraction. The soul does not flee images because they are false. It learns to read them as rays. A face, plant, proportion, melody, colour, or luminous form becomes a reminder of the Ideas. The sensible image becomes a threshold.

The danger is to stop at the threshold. The practice is to let beauty do its work: gather the soul, purify the eye, awaken likeness, and draw perception toward its source.

