The imaginal lesson is simple: the visible world is neither final nor false. It is derivative. Its beauty is real because it participates in a higher beauty. But because it is derivative, it must be followed beyond itself.

Plotinus gives us the ascetic version of imaginal practice. Do not merely collect beautiful images. Ask what in the soul responds to them. Ask what likeness they awaken. Ask what must be carved away for the seeing eye to become sunlike.

The work is not to make the world magical by fantasy.

The work is to become capable of seeing why it was luminous already.

