The Doors of Perception — Blake and the Cleansing of Vision

Commentary

Blake begins by breaking the moral architecture of the world. Heaven and Hell are not treated as fixed moral territories, but as forces inside perception: Reason and Energy, restraint and desire, law and fire. His aim is not to invert morality for shock. It is to free vision from the prison of inherited categories.

For Blake, the world is already infinite. The problem is not that reality lacks spirit. The problem is that perception has narrowed itself until it sees only fragments through a crack in the cave wall.

