Commentary

Blake’s imaginal method is violence against dead perception. The poem does not explain; it shocks. It sets Heaven and Hell into motion, breaks their conventional meanings, and forces the reader to feel energy where they expected evil.

This is why Blake belongs beside Corbin and Jung, though his tone is different. He is also restoring a faculty. But where Corbin carefully distinguishes imaginal from imaginary, Blake uses prophetic reversal. He tears open the inherited world so that perception can become infinite again.

The first act is not belief. It is cleansing.

