The Body as Soul

Commentary

The body not as prison, but as the visible edge of soul.

Commentary

Blake’s statement that the body is a portion of soul is one of the strongest anti-dualist gestures in visionary literature. He does not separate spiritual vision from embodied energy. The senses are not enemies of the soul; they are inlets of soul.

This gives a different imaginal path from ascetic withdrawal. Blake does not say: leave the body to find spirit. He says: the body itself has been misperceived. Desire, energy, sensation, and imagination are not obstacles by default. They become distorted when governed by fear and dead law.

The body is imaginal when it is perceived as soul’s surface.

