The proverbs are not advice in the ordinary sense. They are engines of re-rendering. Each one strikes a fixed category and makes it move. Excess, prudence, desire, folly, belief, truth: Blake makes them flare so the reader cannot hold them in their usual place.

This is why his style is so useful for Imaginarium. Blake does not merely describe visionary perception. He performs it. The text itself becomes a furnace in which inherited meanings melt and recombine.

To read Blake properly is to let the sentence injure the dead part of the eye.

