Distance as Difference of State

Commentary

Nearness and distance as spiritual affinity made visible.

Commentary

This is the exact principle Corbin later uses to illuminate Na-koja-Abad. Space exists, but it is not measured externally. It is seen according to the state of interiors.

Two people may stand side by side in the physical world and be distant in the spiritual world. Two souls may be separated by continents and yet be neighbours in state. In the imaginal world, geography is affinity.

This gives the practical instruction: when an inner landscape appears, do not ask only what it depicts. Ask what state it spatialises. What does the distance mean? Why is the guide near? Why is the house inaccessible? Why is the road curved, dark, bright, steep, or blocked?

Spiritual space is the soul seeing its own relations.

