The Place Outside Place — Corbin and the World of the Image

Commentary

Corbin’s essay begins with a wound in Western language. We have the word “imaginary,” but it usually means unreal. Corbin needs another word because the Islamic philosophers and visionaries he is reading are not describing fantasy. They are describing a real order of being, reached by a real organ of perception.

The imaginal is not make-believe. It is the middle world where soul, symbol, angel, city, body, and landscape become visible.

