Orientation: Read the opening where Corbin distinguishes the imaginal from the merely imaginary and names the “eighth climate” as a real order of perception.

Citation: Henry Corbin, Mundus Imaginalis, or the Imaginary and the Imaginal, Hermetic Library edition.

Image

The Eighth Climate

Commentary

A cosmological image of the world as layered, symbolic, and upheld by invisible orders.

Commentary

Corbin then turns to Suhrawardī’s Na-koja-Abad, the “land of No-where.” This sounds like utopia, but Corbin insists it is the opposite. Utopia is nowhere because it has no reality. Na-koja-Abad is No-where because it is not contained inside physical space.

This is the first major re-rendering. The imaginal world is not found by travelling farther across the map. It is found by changing the mode of space itself. The road does not lead outward. It leads inward, and then the inward becomes the greater outside.

