The cosmic mountain as threshold between sensory geography and psychocosmic geography.

Commentary

The mountain of Qaf is not a fantasy mountain. It marks the limit of ordinary orientation. To pass beyond Qaf is to pass beyond the “where” that belongs to the senses.

Corbin’s point is exact: the visionary does not abolish form. He enters a subtler form. The imaginal world still has cities, colours, extension, bodies, meetings, distances. But these are not physical properties. They are spiritual states made spatial.

