The First Living Image

Commentary

A symbolic image becoming inwardly alive rather than merely mentally pictured.

The first movement is remarkably subtle. Steiner does not tell the student to seek visions. He asks for a different quality of attention. Ordinary thinking gradually becomes freed from dependence upon the senses until it acquires its own vitality. What first appears as symbolic exercise slowly becomes an organ of perception.

The image is therefore not the destination. It is the training ground where thinking learns to move independently.

