The Mobile Human Form

Commentary

The body perceived as a flowing process rather than a fixed object.

One of Steiner's most surprising claims is that imaginative cognition alters both subject and object. The body ceases to appear as static matter. Simultaneously, thinking ceases to behave like abstract analysis.

Both become movement.

This echoes Goethe's science of metamorphosis. Living reality is encountered through transformation rather than fixed definitions. The imaginal faculty therefore perceives becoming before it perceives completed things.

