The Inner Workshop

Commentary

Meditation as a gradual reshaping of the whole soul.

Steiner repeatedly returns to the same principle: higher perception is never added onto an unchanged observer.

The observer changes first.

This makes imaginative cognition fundamentally ethical. The practices are not techniques for collecting visions. They are disciplines that reorder thinking, feeling, and willing until the soul itself becomes capable of receiving realities that were previously inaccessible.

The imaginal world is therefore not hidden because it is distant. It is hidden because ordinary consciousness lacks the corresponding organ.

