The image released so something greater may appear.

Perhaps Steiner's greatest safeguard is that imagination must eventually be relinquished.

The practitioner first learns to cultivate living images. Later, those very images must be consciously released. Only then can inspiration emerge. The imaginal is therefore neither fantasy nor attachment to visionary experience. It is a bridge.

Images educate perception until perception can hear the realities from which the images themselves arise.

The true work of imagination is not to hold us inside pictures, but to carry us beyond them.

