The Soul in the Face of Things — James Hillman and the Return of Anima Mundi

Commentary

James Hillman's essay Anima Mundi: The Return of the Soul to the World marks one of the decisive shifts in archetypal psychology. Rather than asking how the individual can discover the soul within, Hillman asks a more unsettling question: what if the soul has never been confined inside us at all?

Following Plato, Plotinus, Marsilio Ficino, and Henry Corbin, Hillman argues that psychology became impoverished when it withdrew psychic reality from the world. The task is not merely to analyse dreams or inner images, but to recover the world's own imagination—to perceive that every thing presents itself as an image with its own interiority.

