Hillman's reversal is profound. Modern psychology usually begins with the individual psyche and projects outward. Hillman asks us to imagine the opposite movement. The world itself possesses psychic reality. Human consciousness is not the only place where images appear.

The imaginal therefore becomes ecological. Mountains, streets, buildings, weather, rivers, and abandoned objects cease to be neutral matter. They become presences that ask to be perceived aesthetically rather than merely explained scientifically.

