The Aesthetic Compass

Commentary

Beauty and ugliness functioning as orientations of perception rather than merely personal preference.

Hillman restores aesthetics to psychology without reducing beauty to taste.

For Plotinus, whom Hillman follows closely here, beauty signals participation in one's proper order, while ugliness often accompanies a departure into a mode of being foreign to the soul. Hillman transforms this into practical psychology. Our spontaneous aesthetic reactions become clues about psychic alignment.

The imaginal is therefore ethical not because it imposes rules, but because perception itself carries orientation.

