The Ensouled Street

Commentary

The ordinary world encountered as psychologically alive.

Hillman's final movement is perhaps the most radical.

He does not ask us to withdraw from the world in order to discover soul. He asks us to discover that soul has been waiting in the world all along.

The imaginal becomes a discipline of attention. Every encounter—a stone wall, traffic light, abandoned factory, birdcall, window, or gust of wind—can be approached as an imaginal event rather than inert fact.

Psychology ceases to be merely the study of the human mind.

It becomes participation in a living cosmos whose images are already speaking.

