The Angel Who Calls You by Name — Henry Corbin on Avicenna's Visionary Recital

Commentary

Henry Corbin's Avicenna and the Visionary Recital is not merely a study of medieval Islamic philosophy. It is an invitation into a mode of reading where philosophy, visionary experience, and spiritual autobiography become inseparable.

Corbin argues that Avicenna's symbolic recitals are not allegories hiding abstract doctrines. They are maps of consciousness. The landscapes, angels, mountains, birds, kings, and travellers belong to the mundus imaginalis—the intermediate world where the soul encounters realities that are neither physical objects nor subjective fantasies.

This essay follows the opening movement of Corbin's interpretation of Avicenna's Recital of Ḥayy ibn Yaqẓān, guiding the reader through the imaginal geography that unfolds as the Stranger meets the Guide.

